column1: 193012;instagram;2019-01-27 07:45:23;FALSE;"part 1 - ""i was born & raised with religion. prior to islam it was christianity. while i loved the good in my christian faith
column2: the bad was very painful for me. i viewed eternal hell & damnation
column3: satan & his demons & armageddon as psychological torture designed to dominate and control.

column1: my mother was my world and it all came crashing down around me the day she died. the father i barely knew took my sister & i to another state & dumped us off like unwanted pets on a strict southern baptist aunt and uncle i didn‚Äôt know at the time. i was a mentally traumatized & love- starved little girl who had survived abuse at the hands of a crazy catholic grandmother & the sexual predator she married.

my aunt and uncle were the best thing that ever happened to my sister and i - they did their best and i love them dearly for it. they provided some structure & a glimpse of what it would have been like to have parents. with them
column2: i would at least learn to read and i began getting an education
column3: even though my primary education was religion. but we both desperately needed mental and physical medical help. what i got instead was religion
column5: prayers before every meal and bedtime etc. the school had them take me to doctor where it was determined i had a seizure condition. i was even prescribed medicine for it but they chose to leave it to god to heal me instead. they offered a bipolar kind of god that i was supposed to love and fear. i‚Äôd never really known an adult who wasn‚Äôt abusive or neglectful in someway. a dysfunctional & toxic family was what i knew so it wasn‚Äôt hard to imagine a god like that. i think i was 8 the first time someone suggested my mother might be in hell. traumatising horror stories made hell a very real and terrifying place for me.

column1: my teen years were a nightmare of #metoo kind of moments. there was good in my life as well but it was so much more painful and difficult then it should have been.""

column1: 193130;instagram;2019-01-27 12:08:58;FALSE;"it's funny how you keep paying the price for things that were done to you
column2: no matter how long ago. violence has an energy all its own; it attaches itself to you like a cord wrapping tighter and tighter around your being
column3: and no matter how often you cut through the cord or how many pieces you throw away
column4: it never releases its stranglehold on you. somehow you never stop explaining or apologising for what was done to you. as if you are the one to blame.

column1: no matter how often or how deeply you delve into that festering wound
column2: it won't heal. no matter that you work bloody hard to get over it (because you must
column3: don't you know) and allow maggots to eat away at the suppurating flesh... the wound may scab over
column4: but it won't heal. not really. there will never be a shimmering river of gold beautifying something so ugly
column5: like kintsugi fusing porcelain. you keep paying the price.

column1: so what do you do? i guess you learn to live with the inescapable. and knowing this world
column2: there are teeming multitudes of people connected by the same cord that can never be cut away. and as you sink into that knowledge
column3: you remember that you are not the only one
column4: and you were actually one of the lucky ones.

column1: this is why i'm a feminist. this is why i support #metoo
column2: why taking down the patriarchy and the dark heritage of colonialism matters to me
column3: why i share things here that make me cringe and feel ashamed
column4: things that i would like to keep secret and hide because they make me look weak and sad ‚Äî i talk about these things because where there is violence
column5: it is always the victim who ends up with the life sentence. and that must change.

column1: 193407;instagram;2019-01-27 18:47:28;FALSE;"an other my play mate ü§™. this man came out from side of trail in front of me slow sloppy run( i was doing my #sunday #easyrun) and looked at me and suddenly speed up . so decided to match his pace to see how long he could hold the pace. i wanted him acknowledge me and say hi as courtesy

as miss newfoundland and labrador world 2019
column2: and hopefully as the next miss world canada
column3: i want to highlight issues facing women today
column4: especially issues surrounding sexual and domestic violence. when i was competing in miss teenage canada
column5: i was in a not-so-great relationship. it was abusive. and part of the reason i stayed for so long was because i felt like i didn‚Äôt deserve any better. then
column6: i spent a week in toronto with a group of incredibly talented and accomplished young women and realized my own worth
column7: and gained the confidence to get out of the unhealthy relationship i was in. miss teenage canada saved me from having a life i never would have wanted. i found something i loved doing that made me happy and confident again
column8: so i‚Äôm really excited to be representing my province nationally once again
column9: this time at miss world canada. i just wanted to share my story to let other women know that if you‚Äôre in an unhealthy
column11: that you deserve better and you‚Äôre worthy of something better.  sharing this on instagram is kind of scary
column12: and i wrote a blog post about it on my website (which was a little less scary because it has a much smaller following)
column13: but i just want other women to know that they‚Äôre not alone in these experiences and i hope this might inspire someone who‚Äôs struggling right now to leave if they‚Äôre in a bad situation.

column2: i have reflected on my own experiences with sexual harassment in the workplace and academia. it is frustrating to know there is an infrastructure that protects (mainly) men  and demonizes the victims. it's not just r&b

a survey conducted by the veterinary information network (a large web based vet professional community) found that over 40% of responders had experienced and witnessed sexual harassment in the workplace. over 2

column2: i say something...and i keep a record of it. do your best to hold your employer accountable. you shouldn't need to ""tough it out.""‚†Ä

column2: in my very first column for the daily pennsylvanian
column3: i wrote about aziz ansari and my views on the nascent #metoo movement.¬† in the past year
column7: and finally slight waves of despair
column8: as the movement faded from a dominant cultural phenomenon to second-rate news. in some ways
column12: it feels like the promise of the movement has dissolved into empty gestures and performative rhetoric
column13: while the predatory men the movement outed crawl back into public life. the ansari story was a particular flashpoint during the waves of allegations about sexual harassment and assault that seemed to come in a never-ending flood last winter. unlike the allegations against others named in the movement
column18: the allegations against ansari were not part of a documented pattern of workplace misconduct and harassment. instead
column19: it was a stand alone account about a date between two single adults that went‚Ä¶

column1: 193992;instagram;2019-01-28 10:32:29;FALSE;"former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel
column2: but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

column1: in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23
column2: flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia
column3: and kushner spoke with kim darroch
column4: the british ambassador to the united states
column5: according to diplomats familiar with the conversations
column6: who spoke on condition of anonymity.

column1: the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump
column2: who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric
column3: took office on jan. 20. it failed
column4: with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

column1: the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move
column2: egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution
column3: prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

column1: a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a ""high level"" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.
according to court documents made public on friday
column2: a member of trump's presidential transition team
column3: later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner
column4: told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments
column6: to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.
